          bigtophero
"></div><p> 7 月 26 日，尼日尔精锐总统卫队官员<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apparent-coup-attempt-hits-u-s-ally-niger-e3efa36d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">拘留了西非国家当选总统</a>穆罕默德·巴祖姆，并宣布自己为该国新领导人。这次政变令美国和欧洲政府感到震惊，这些国家一直<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-russia-africa-86cf1454?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与巴祖姆和尼日尔军队密切合作</a>，打击非洲萨赫勒地区的伊斯兰武装分子。</p><p>尼日尔的一些西非邻国（主要<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与美国和欧洲结盟</a>）威胁要使用武力恢复巴祖姆的地位。其他<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与俄罗斯结盟的</a>国家则表示，他们将捍卫尼日尔的新军政府。</p><h3>美国和欧洲政府为何担心尼日尔政变？</h3><p>尼日尔一直是美国和欧洲<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">打击基地组织和伊斯兰国武装分子</a>的中心，这些武装分子近年来在撒哈拉以南的半干旱地区萨赫勒地区杀害了数千人。在马里和布基纳法索军方领导的政府驱逐了一直在那里与伊斯兰叛乱分子作战的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-embassy-evacuation-africa-33d18bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">法国和其他西方军队</a>后，尼日尔变得更加重要。美国已花费约 5 亿美元武装尼日尔军队，配备从帐篷、收音机到侦察机和装甲运兵车等各种装备。美国在尼日尔驻有约 1,100 名士兵，他们训练当地特种部队并为他们执行任务提供建议。法国在尼日尔驻有大约 1,500 名士兵。</p><p>欧盟还依赖世界上最贫穷国家之一的尼日尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-considers-substantial-fund-for-africa-to-deal-with-migrants-1440871414?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">来阻止非洲移民</a>进入利比亚并从那里进入欧盟。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="819" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828956?width=1260&amp;height=819" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">政变支持者在尼亚美示威期间悬挂俄罗斯国旗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>什么是西共体？它能扭转政变吗？</h3><p>西非国家经济共同体是一个由 15 个西非国家组成的政治和经济组织，其中包括尼日利亚、加纳和塞内加尔等地区重量级国家。 7 月 30 日，西非经共体 11 名领导人在紧急峰会上向尼日尔新军政府提出了 7 天的期限，要求释放巴祖姆并让他重新担任总统。此后，该组织领导人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁要对尼日尔发动军事干预</a>，以恢复巴祖姆的权力。他们还对尼日尔实施了一系列严厉的金融和贸易制裁，希望迫使军政府做出让步。这些制裁包括冻结尼日尔在地区中央银行的资产以及切断尼日利亚的电力供应。尼日尔约 75% 的电力从非洲最大经济体、尼日尔南部邻国尼日利亚购买。</p><p>作为回应，马里和布基纳法索的政变也受到西非经共体的谴责，它们警告说，他们将把对尼日尔的武装干预视为宣战，并将保卫尼亚美军政府。</p><p>随着西非经共体 8 月 6 日最后期限的临近，越来越多的人反对对尼日利亚进行干预，因为尼日利亚必须领导这样的任务。当地政界人士和媒体指出，尼日利亚军方正在努力遏制国内的伊斯兰叛乱分子、土匪和其他安全威胁。</p><p>分析人士警告说，干预可能会将迄今为止的不流血政变变成导致许多平民死亡的地区冲突。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828965?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">欧洲和美国公民从尼日尔撤离后抵达罗马附近的机场。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：雷莫·卡西利/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>美国如何回应？</h3><p>拜登总统和国务卿安东尼·布林肯</p>呼吁释放巴祖姆并保护尼日尔的民主。 8月4日，美国政府效仿欧洲各国政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-pause-some-financial-aid-to-niger-as-country-reels-from-coup-7252caa1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">暂停了对尼日尔的部分财政援助，</a>以向军政府施加压力。尼日尔近一半的预算来自外国援助，其中大部分来自西方政府。<p></p><p>然而，美国官员一直小心翼翼地避免将军方的行动称为政变，这一名称将引发美国法律<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对军事援助的限制</a>。国防部表示，没有计划将军事人员或装备撤出尼日尔，并支持通过外交途径解决局势。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=2AE037D3-6705-43B5-828C-C117387FADDD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-coup-president-us-fumble-russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">尼日尔上周发生政变后，欧洲各国政府和美国下令从尼日尔撤离本国公民。军政府领导人表示，军方不会屈服于压力，要求让被罢黜的总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆复职。照片：萨姆·梅德尼克/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>拜登政府尚未表示美国是否会为西非经共体可能对尼日尔进行的军事干预提供后勤或其他支持。布林肯 8 月 3 日表示：“我们支持西非经共体的努力，包括施压。”美国官员对西非经共体的军事干预表示怀疑，部分原因是担心平民死亡——包括可能包括被俘总统本人的死亡——并表示他们更喜欢和平解决方案。</p><p> 8月7日，代理副国务卿维多利亚·纽兰前往尼日尔，与尼日尔政变领导人穆萨·萨劳·巴尔穆将军及其顾问进行了两个多小时的会谈。巴尔穆曾在尼日尔<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-builds-new-firewall-to-stop-spread-of-militant-islamists-11670771719?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">与美国特种部队密切合作</a>。</p><p> “我希望他们保持外交大门敞开。我们提出了这个建议......他们对于如何推进有自己的想法，”纽兰周一告诉记者。 “他们的想法不符合宪法，如果他们走这条路，我们的关系就会很困难。但我们给了他们一些继续谈话的选择，我们希望他们接受我们的建议。”</p><p>她说，她多次要求与巴祖姆会面，但都被拒绝了。</p><p>美国国务院已下令<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/state-department-orders-partial-evacuation-of-u-s-embassy-in-niger-48bcb7bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">撤离美国驻尼亚美大使馆的所有非必要人员</a>以及美国大使馆工作人员的家属。与法国不同的是，美国尚未从尼日尔全面撤离美国公民。法国已向尼日尔派遣了多架撤侨航班，并表示已帮助约 40 名美国公民离开该国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828970?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼日尔总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆与美国和欧洲政府密切合作，打击伊斯兰激进分子。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路透社/媒体库</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>奥马尔·查尼将军是谁？</h3><p>尊敬的奥马尔·查尼将军，</p>有时也被称为阿卜杜拉哈曼 (Abdourahamane)，是发动反对巴祖姆起义的总统卫队首领。他现在作为尼日尔自封的领导人领导军政府。据熟悉尼日尔局势的人士透露，巴祖姆一直在考虑是否解雇蒂亚尼，这是政变的触发因素之一。 <p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="390" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829050?width=700&amp;height=390" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">军政府首脑、尼日尔自称领导人奥马尔·查尼将军率领总统卫队发动了政变。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ORTN/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3><strong>尼日尔军政府想要什么？</strong></h3><p>奇亚尼和其他军政府成员都提到了尼日尔不断恶化的安全局势。然而，根据非营利性武装冲突地点和事件数据项目的数据，2023 年上半年，尼日尔针对平民的袭击减少了 49%，而造成的死亡人数与前六个月相比下降了 16%。 Acled 数据显示，去年尼日尔发生了 114 起圣战组织袭击事件。</p><p>军政府尚未就其与莫斯科的关系发表任何公开声明，但其早期行动表明它可能会脱离西方。 8月3日晚，它宣布<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-end-military-cooperation-with-france-deepening-concerns-over-anti-western-turn-e7fae57e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">终止与法国的军事合作</a>，包括授权法国军队留在该国。法国外交部表示，不承认军政府的权威，也没有撤军计划。奇亚尼还派遣一名副手前往马里与该国亲俄罗斯领导人进行会谈。</p><h3><strong>俄罗斯对尼日尔政变持何立场？</strong></h3><p>俄罗斯政府呼吁尼日尔恢复宪法秩序，并警告不要进行武装干预。叶夫根尼·普里戈津（Yevgeny Prigozhin）的准军事瓦格纳集团已经在马里拥有战士，他赞扬了这次政变，并向尼亚美军政府提供了他的雇佣军服务。</p><p>法国外交部长指责俄罗斯的虚假信息导致了针对其大使馆的支持政变的抗议活动。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —William Mauldin 和 Vivian Salama 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟 (Gabriele Steinhauser)，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 22:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-Russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-Russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc<author><![CDATA[Gabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>奥马尔·齐亚尼</category><category>穆罕默德·巴祖姆</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Argentina’s Ruling Peronists Await Defeat in Sunday Primary]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>民意调查显示，在通货膨胀率高达 116% 且货币疲软的情况下，该国考虑保守、有利于商业的候选人<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116967"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831073?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">自由党候选人哈维尔·米雷承诺将阿根廷经济美元化并关闭该国中央银行。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马蒂亚斯·巴列托/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116967"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">瑞安·杜贝</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日下午 6:16 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-ruling-peronists-await-defeat-in-sunday-primary-fa5d99ef"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>民意调查显示，随着阿根廷通胀率突破100%且货币快速贬值，预计选民将在周日对执政的庇隆主义运动提出谴责，该运动在过去75年的大部分时间里一直统治着该国。</p><p>根据民意调查机构 Opinaia 的数据，总统阿尔贝托·费尔南德斯 (Alberto Fernández) 的支持率为 75%，他今年早些时候表示不会寻求连任。在周日的初选中，阿根廷人预计将把最多选票投给一个亲商的反对党，该党的候选人承诺削减公共支出，根据民意调查和预测，公共支出导致通货膨胀率达到 116%，位居全球最高之列。政治分析家。</p><p>这次投票正值这个拥有4600万人口的国家陷入二十年来最严重的经济危机之际，这让人与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1008839567321991160?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阿根廷2001年的金融危机</a>相提并论，当时阿根廷在暴力街头抗议中两周内更换了五位总统。布宜诺斯艾利斯民意调查机构 Poliarquía 主任亚历杭德罗·卡特伯格 (Alejandro Catterberg) 表示，由于通货膨胀和经济停滞，阿根廷有五分之四的家庭削减了支出。根据政府统计机构的数据，大约 40% 的人口处于贫困状态。</p><p> “阿根廷的局势非常严峻，”卡特伯格说。 “愤怒、愤怒、幻灭和沮丧，这些就是阿根廷社会的感受。”</p><p>前总统毛里西奥·马克里领导的联合变革联盟有两名候选人：中间派布宜诺斯艾利斯市长奥拉西奥·罗德里格斯·拉雷塔和保守派前国会议员帕特里夏·布尔里奇，后者以严厉打击犯罪政策而闻名。</p><p>极右翼自由主义者哈维尔·米雷承诺将阿根廷经济美元化并关闭该国中央银行，他也利用多年来经济停滞、高通胀和贫困加剧后对阿根廷政治体制的明显愤怒而获得了强有力的支持。</p><p>初选是 10 月 22 日普选之前衡量全国候选人支持度的关键指标，因为阿根廷人需要在初选中投票。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="472" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831080?width=700&amp;height=472" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">六月的抗议活动中，人们聚集在布宜诺斯艾利斯总统府附近。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：MIGUEL LO BIANCO/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>费尔南德斯领导的庇隆主义政党遭到如此明显的拒绝，以至于一个实行货币和价格管制的联盟提出了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-s-president-names-sergio-massa-as-new-economy-minister-11659044057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">经济部长塞尔吉奥·马萨作为候选人，</a>经济学家认为这些管制对企业造成了伤害，他被认为是一个温和派，比总统更亲商。和其他领导人。</p><p>布宜诺斯艾利斯托尔库阿托迪特拉大学经济学家巴勃罗·吉多蒂表示，在政府被迫向国际货币基金组织的救助计划提供再融资后，他预计今年阿根廷经济将收缩3%。</p><p> “我们能期望的最好结果就是政府能够避免一场重大的金融危机，”他说。 “经济将持续到选举前，通胀高企，经济活动停滞。”</p><p>上个月，国际货币基金组织同意向阿根廷拨款 75 亿美元，这是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/imf-executive-board-to-meet-soon-to-vote-on-argentina-bailout-1528382633?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">440 亿美元救助计划</a>的一部分。</p><p>该国最初在马克里执政期间接受了救助，马克里在 2015-2019 年任期内<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gradualism-is-dead-argentina-faces-pressure-to-hasten-economic-overhaul-1527586201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">试图逐步减少从其前任、庇隆主义领导人兼副总统克里斯蒂娜·基什内尔继承的公共支出</a>，</p>而不是冒着社会动荡的风险采取严厉的紧缩措施。形势如此危急，阿根廷向卡塔尔寻求帮助以偿还债务，卡塔尔向费尔南德斯政府提供了 7.65 亿美元的信贷额度。阿根廷还向中国和总部位于委内瑞拉的拉丁美洲开发银行提供贷款。<p></p><p>吉多蒂表示，如果中右翼候选人这次获胜，政府将被迫更快地实施改革，以解除货币管制和削减赤字。</p><p> “他们无法承受逐步调整的代价，”他说。 “他们需要从一开始就进行认真的改革。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="468" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831081?width=700&amp;height=468" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿根廷的货币正在快速贬值。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：奥古斯丁·马尔卡里安/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>密切关注该国的分析师表示，尽管对现状感到愤怒，但很少有阿根廷人会接受如果实施广泛的改革，短期内预计会出现更多的经济困难。</p><p>阿根廷专家​​、威尔逊中心主任本杰明·格丹表示：“反对派认为，阿根廷人现在对三位数的通货膨胀感到非常沮丧，他们愿意承担削减预算的负担，以摆脱通货膨胀的螺旋式上升。”华盛顿拉丁美洲计划。 “我只是认为事实并非如此。”</p><p>去年，马萨在被任命为经济部长后不久<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentina-will-stick-to-imf-targets-to-reduce-budget-deficit-11663029891?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">承诺恢复财政稳定</a>和促进出口，导致政府未能实现国际货币基金组织减少预算赤字和建立接近于零的央行储备的目标。</p><p>但马萨表示，由于严重干旱影响了农产品出口并导致黑市比索大幅贬值，与国际金融市场隔绝的政府难以遏制印钞。</p><p> “我们的出口损失了 34 亿美元，”马萨在周一接受电台采访时说道，他在其中解释了经济挑战。</p><p>这种困难导致前公务员丹妮拉·托斯卡诺(Daniela Toscano)等阿根廷人在发现收支平衡越来越困难后离开了这个国家。</p><p> “我没有返回阿根廷的计划，”她在 2020 年搬到迈阿密时说道。“我为了我的未来、为了我的幸福而离开了我的国家，因为如果你留在阿根廷，你就无法进步，你陷入困境，日复一日地生活。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Silvina Frydlewsky 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Ryan Dubé： <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 22:16:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-ruling-peronists-await-defeat-in-sunday-primary-fa5d99ef</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-ruling-peronists-await-defeat-in-sunday-primary-fa5d99ef<author><![CDATA[Ryan Dubé]]></author><category>分析师的评论/建议</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>分析师评论</category><category>建议</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算</category><category>税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Saudi Aramco’s Profit Drops, Hit by Lower Oil Prices, Output]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>多数国有石油巨头将股息增加一半以上，提振利雅得的财政<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115133"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="550" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830707?width=860&amp;height=550" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">沙特阿美的股息承诺一直是沙特政府的主要资金来源，也是能源投资者的风向标。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马克西姆·谢梅托夫/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115133"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/summer-said" itemprop="url" rel="author">夏天说</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 7 日下午 6:04（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-aramcos-profit-drops-hit-by-lower-oil-prices-output-9ce157e5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>由于能源价格下跌和减产，沙特阿拉伯国家石油公司公布的季度利润下降了 38%，但股息增加了一半以上，凸显了该国对石油收入的依赖。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SA/XSAU/2222" class="">沙特阿拉伯石油公司</a><span class="company-name-type">（</span>简称阿美公司）周一表示，截至6月30日的季度，其净利润从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-aramco-posts-record-161-billion-profit-in-2022-d7c99a6a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">去年同期的</a>484.4亿美元降至1128.1亿沙特里亚尔，约合300.8亿美元，而去年同期受益于油价飙升。俄罗斯入侵乌克兰后。</p><p>第二季度利润略高于阿美公司提供的调查中 15 名分析师预期的 298 亿美元，是该公司自<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aramco-expected-to-value-energy-giant-at-1-7-trillion-in-ipo-11575559262?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2019 年 12 月上市</a>以来收入第三大降幅。上一次季度利润大幅下降是在 2020 年，当时油价因 Covid-19 大流行而暴跌。沙特阿美是全球最有价值的公司之一，市值约为 2 万亿美元，去年一度取代苹果公司位居榜首。</p><p>今年早些时候，由于担心全球经济放缓将抑制需求以及俄罗斯廉价原油供应的大量涌入，油价处于较低水平。该公司表示，该公司的利润还受到炼油和化学品利润疲软的影响。</p><p>国际石油基准布伦特原油继 7 月份上涨 13%、创一年半以来最大月度涨幅后，已稳稳回升至每桶 80 美元以上。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-08-07-2023?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">周一</a>上涨 0.7%，至 85.91 美元。</p><p>沙特阿美表示，第二季度的股息支付总额将为294亿美元，其中包括与业绩挂钩的部分，高于一年前的188亿美元定期股息，原因是国际石油公司在利润下降的情况下仍采取措施增加对股东的派息。由沙特政府持有多数股权的沙特阿美公司5月表示，将根据公司的自由现金流，发放与其年度财务业绩挂钩的额外股息。</p><p>沙特阿美的股息承诺一直是沙特政府的主要资金来源，也是能源投资者的风向标——该公司承诺支付巨额经常性股息，以吸引投资者参与其拖延已久的 2019 年首次公开募股。该公司正在谈判中知情人士称，与银行合作，通过二次上市出售更多股票来筹集现金。沙特阿美和政府均未对该计划发表评论。</p><p>该公司表示，自由现金流从上一年的 346.1 亿美元降至 231.6 亿美元。</p><p>罗宾米尔斯表示，阿美公司的自由现金流仍然强劲，</p>迪拜咨询公司 Qamar Energy 的首席执行官，但他预计，除非油价和产量增加，否则该公司将不得不削减基于业绩的股息或增加借款。<p></p><p>尽管如此，提高股息的决定还是引发了人们的疑问：这家石油巨头能否平衡其主要股东的需求与上市公司的投资要求。</p><p>由于原油价格下跌以及炼油和化学品利润疲软，上半年净利润较去年同期下降近30%至619.6亿美元。</p><p>与2022年的丰收相比，全球石油公司的利润下降了约一半，当时俄罗斯入侵乌克兰导致石油和天然气价格飙升。沙特阿美股价今年上涨超过 10%，周一上涨 1.1%，至每股 8.70 美元。</p><p>今年 3 月，沙特阿美公布 2022 年年度利润达到创纪录的 1610 亿美元，这是能源公司有史以来最大的利润，巩固了沙特作为全球最重要石油生产国的主导地位。</p><p>石油繁荣在一定程度上刺激了沙特阿拉伯奉行与美国经常不一致的外交政策和经济利益的意愿<strong>&nbsp;</strong>去年，作为石油输出国组织事实上的领导者的沙特拒绝了美国提出的增加石油产量以抑制不断飙升的原油价格的请求。</p><p>利雅得周四表示，继7月和8月减产100万桶/日以提振油价之后，该国将把每天100万桶石油的减产计划延长至9月。这一决定表明沙特阿拉伯<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-charts-solo-path-on-opec-policy-ab9a436c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">愿意采取对其有利的单方面行动</a>。</p><p>作为欧佩克最大的出口国，沙特阿拉伯希望将油价维持在为王储提供资金所需的水平</p>穆罕默德·本·萨勒曼重塑其依赖石油的经济的雄心勃勃的计划。石油销售是沙特政府最大的收入来源。<p></p><p>沙特的日常统治者穆罕默德亲王在国内开始了大规模的发展计划，启动了一些大型项目，沙特人称其为“超级项目”。去年俄罗斯入侵乌克兰后，油价升至每桶 100 美元，沙特王国加快了这些努力。</p><p>沙特经济顾问近几个月私下警告高级政策制定者，该国需要在未来五年内提高油价，才能继续在迄今为止吸引微薄外国投资的项目上花费数十亿美元。分析师估计，沙特需要将油价维持在每桶 80 美元以上，才能为王储的经济改革计划提供资金。</p><p>海湾地区以前曾经历过石油繁荣，当时原油价格升至每桶 100 美元以上，君主们向从未完成的白象项目投资了数十亿美元，并向公民发放现金以购买支持。过去，当物价暴跌时，沙特阿拉伯采取了紧缩措施。官员和经济学家表示，这次繁荣是不同的，因为它发生在一些海湾国家开始经济自由化的背景下。</p><p>凯投宏观(Capital Economics)副首席新兴市场经济学家贾森·图维(Jason Tuvey)表示，最近的数据显示沙特预算已连续第三个季度陷入赤字，政府显然正在尽最大努力——通过派息——以确保石油收入的下滑不会影响其财政计划。</p><p>目前尚不清楚单方面减产最终将如何影响沙特的收入。尽管油价已升至三个月高点，但减产措施使沙特阿拉伯的产量降至每天900万桶，这是2021年6月以来的最低水平，也是过去10年来罕见的。</p><p>沙特统计总局最新数据显示，5 月份沙特石油出口量已较去年同期下降近 40%。该机构表示，5 月份石油出口额从去年的 308 亿美元下降至约 192 亿美元。</p><p>由于长期减产，国际货币基金组织上个月将沙特阿拉伯 2023 年的增长预测从 2022 年的近 9% 下调至 1.9%。</p><p>沙特阿美公司上调了除北美以外所有地区 9 月份的官方售价，其中针对西北欧的油品涨幅最高。尽管几家亚洲炼油商要求沙特阿美公司在大部分牌号连续两个月上调OSP后，要求展期或削减OSP差异，但价格上涨仍在意料之中。</p><p>写信给 Summer Said： <a href="mailto:summer.said@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">summer.said@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 22:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-aramcos-profit-drops-hit-by-lower-oil-prices-output-9ce157e5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-aramcos-profit-drops-hit-by-lower-oil-prices-output-9ce157e5<author><![CDATA[Summer Said]]></author><category>活力</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>综合石油/天然气</category><category>油和气</category><category>油</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>股息</category><category>输出/生产</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>商品市场</category><category>能源市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>原油市场</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>沙特阿拉伯石油公司</category><category>2222.SA</category><category> SA：2222</category><category>罗宾·米尔斯</category><category>杰森·图维</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>股息</category><category>输出</category><category>生产</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>服务</category><category>商品市场</category><category>能源市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>原油市场</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>活力</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>综合油</category><category>气体</category><category>油和气</category><category>油</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Killing of Palestinian Highlights Divide in Israel]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>对被占领的约旦河西岸发生的杀戮事件的不同反应凸显了分歧<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116140"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831134?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">哀悼者抬着一名 19 岁巴勒斯坦人的尸体，这名巴勒斯坦人上周在被占领的约旦河西岸被枪杀。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：jaafar ashtiyeh/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116140"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">多夫·利伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日下午 2:55 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/violence-between-israeli-settlers-and-palestinians-pits-netanyahu-allies-against-security-agencies-581c3f76"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>特拉维夫——周五，当一名犹太牧羊人带着他的羊群去被占领的约旦河西岸的巴勒斯坦村庄布尔卡附近吃草时，暴力事件随之而来。一名 19 岁的巴勒斯坦人被枪杀，一名被指控杀害他的以色列定居者因被石头击中头部受伤住院。</p><p>接下来发生的事情表明，随着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-bank-violence-flares-as-israelis-palestinians-meet-to-calm-tensions-dec3f46?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">以色列人和巴勒斯坦人之间的</a>紧张局势升级，以色列变得多么两极分化。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-far-right-leader-ben-gvir-to-take-important-security-role-in-new-government-11669390931?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">负责监督该国警察部队</a>的极端民族主义政党成员、国家安全部长伊塔马尔·本-格维尔表示，应该向受伤的犹太男子颁发一枚奖章。他在推特上写道：“保护自己和他人免遭巴勒斯坦人谋杀的犹太人并不是谋杀嫌疑人。”</p><p>前国防部长兼军事首长、反对派议员本尼·甘茨反驳说，定居者正在从事一种“危险的犹太恐怖主义”，这种活动正在转移该国的安全资源，并使以色列人的生命处于危险之中。他说，对杀手的支持是“一个无法抹去的污点”。</p><p>总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡的联合政府包括极端民族主义政党，他们支持扩大犹太人在西岸的主权，并将定居者的暴力事件定性为自卫。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="459" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831131?width=700&amp;height=459" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">最近，一名以色列士兵在约旦河西岸。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Nasser Ishtayeh/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这让他们与以色列安全机构的部分人士产生了分歧，后者表示，以色列需要采取更多措施来阻止犹太定居者日益增长的暴力浪潮，否则特拉维夫和耶路撒冷等城市将面临遭到报复的风险。</p><p> “毫无疑问，这些事情正在将[约旦河西岸]未参与恐怖主义的人们推向恐怖主义，”以色列军方发言人丹尼尔·哈加里(Daniel Hagari)周一在接受新闻网站Ynet采访时表示。</p><p>美国国务院采取了不同寻常的步骤，将这次杀戮称为“以色列极端主义定居者的恐怖袭击”，并敦促“全面问责和伸张正义”，这加剧了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-ambassador-warned-israel-against-going-off-the-rails-with-judicial-overhaul-d612fffa?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国和以色列之间的紧张关系</a>，两国关系因内塔尼亚胡的计划而紧张。司法改革。</p><p>分析人士称，内塔尼亚胡联盟中的极端民族主义者和定居者代表指责军方和其他官员站在巴勒斯坦人一边，扩大了以色列国家堡垒与现任政府方向之间的分歧。</p><p>随着定居者寻求在西岸扩张，犹太定居者与巴勒斯坦人之间的暴力冲突不断增加。根据以色列安全机构的数据，今年前六个月的事件数量几乎与 2022 年全年一样多。</p><p>联合国称，以色列定居者今年杀害了七名巴勒斯坦人，其中四人没有参与冲突。去年，有两人被杀。</p><p>就以色列人而言，他们面临着更多的巴勒斯坦暴力，包括周六晚上特拉维夫发生的枪击事件，导致一名以色列市政安全官员死亡。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831140?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">以色列国家安全部长伊塔马尔·本格维尔最近在被占领的约旦河西岸。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ahmad gharabli/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-benjamin-netanyahus-win-in-israel-the-rise-of-religious-zionism-11667743595?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">宗教犹太复国主义和犹太权力党</a>的成员——许多来自以色列西岸定居点——在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-benjamin-netanyahu-returns-to-power-in-sixth-term-as-prime-minister-11672324590?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">内塔尼亚胡去年年底组建的新政府</a>中形成了一个关键集团，现在控制着监督以色列在那里存在的关键要素的职位。</p><p>周五暴力事件发生后不久，由数百名前以色列高级安全官员组成的伞式组织“以色列安全指挥官”发表声明称，实施袭击的定居者“坚信自己凌驾于法律之上”。</p><p>以色列国内安全机构负责人辛贝特 (Shin Bet) 7 月底在与以色列高级官员的谈话中警告说，定居者的暴力行为正在助长巴勒斯坦人对以色列人的袭击。作为回应，一些联盟成员指责巴尔站在巴勒斯坦人一边。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡周一致电巴尔，告诉他他支持安全机构及其为保护以色列公民所做的工作。</p><p>本-格维尔于 2007 年因煽动种族主义和支持犹太恐怖组织而被定罪，在从政之前，他经常为被指控对巴勒斯坦人犯下罪行的定居者提供法律辩护，作为定居者运动的捍卫者，他的影响力正在与日俱增。</p><p>耶胡达·利伯 (Yehuda Lieber) 说：“我真的很珍视并感谢这个政府，它比之前摧毁这个地方的政府要好。”</p>他住在奥兹锡安（Oz Zion），这是星期五事件发生的巴勒斯坦村庄附近的一个定居者前哨基地。 “我相信本-格维尔会明白谁是恐怖分子，以及是谁为保卫他的生命而战。” <p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831143?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">反对派议员本尼·甘茨表示，定居者的行为正在转移以色列的安全资源。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿米尔·科恩/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>利伯说，他和其他定居者打算在约旦河西岸尽可能多的空地定居，并将其视为与决心这样做的巴勒斯坦人的一场竞赛。</p><p>周五被杀的 19 岁巴勒斯坦人库赛·穆坦 (Qusay Mu’tan) 的叔叔里夫基·穆坦 (Rifki Mu’tan) 表示，村民们很熟悉那个带着羊群到他们家附近吃草的牧羊人，并指责他试图阻止他们进入他们自己的土地。</p><p>村民们表示，Oz Zion 前哨基地建在他们的私人土地上，而该地区巴勒斯坦土地上的早期定居点已于 2012 年以色列最高法院做出裁决后撤离。</p><p>巴勒斯坦和以色列权利组织表示，定居者经常试图在西岸饲养牲畜，以获取大片未定居土地的权利。穆坦说，牧羊人此前曾威胁要烧毁他们的村庄，今年早些时候其他村庄的定居者也采用了这一策略。</p><p> “他们一直用纵火威胁我们，”另一位布尔卡居民艾哈迈德·阿卜杜勒卡里姆 (Ahmad Abdelkarim) 说。</p><p>随着紧张局势加剧，这里的政治分析人士将注意力转向这可能如何影响以色列与阿拉伯国家和美国政府的关系。</p><p>以色列巴伊兰大学美以关系专家、耶路撒冷战略与安全研究所高级研究员埃坦·吉尔博亚表示，拜登政府急于将周五的杀戮定性为恐怖袭击，反映出华盛顿对内塔尼亚胡的无能日益感到沮丧。或者不愿意缓和日益增长的暴力。</p><p>吉尔博亚说：“美国无法回答的根本问题是，是他控制着他的联盟，还是他的联盟控制着他。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Fatima AbdulKarim 和 Ari Flanzraich 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 18:55:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/violence- Between-israeli-settlers-and-palestinians-pits-netanyahu-allies-against-security-agcies-581c3f76</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/violence- Between-israeli-settlers-and-palestinians-pits-netanyahu-allies-against-security-agcies-581c3f76<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国家安全措施/政策</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>伊塔玛·本·格维尔</category><category>本尼·甘茨</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>丹尼尔·哈加里</category><category>罗南酒吧</category><category>耶胡达·利伯</category><category>里夫基·穆坦</category><category>库赛·穆坦</category><category>艾哈迈德·阿卜杜勒卡里姆</category><category>埃坦·吉尔博亚</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>政治</category><category>国家安全措施</category><category>政策</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tesla CFO Zach Kirkhorn Steps Down Ahead of Cybertruck Launch]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公司资深人士被视为埃隆·马斯克(Elon Musk)首席执行官的可能继任者<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115434"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="484" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830811?width=860&amp;height=484" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">扎克·柯克霍恩（左）和埃隆·马斯克在今年的特斯拉投资者日。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：特斯拉</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115434"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rebecca-elliott" itemprop="url" rel="author">丽贝卡·埃利奥特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 7 日中午 12:17（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">特斯拉</a>首席财务官扎克·科克霍恩 (Zach Kirkhorn) 在担任该职位四年多后辞职，他在幕后工作，将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk</a> ) 的雄心壮志变为现实。</p><p>这家电动汽车制造商周一表示，首席会计官 Vaibhav Taneja 已于 8 月 4 日被任命为首席财务官，随后 Kirkhorn 离职。</p><p>他的这一出人意料的举动是在特斯拉的 Cyber​​truck 皮卡今年晚些时候上市之前做出的，这引发了人们对马斯克继任计划的质疑。马斯克现年 52 岁，经营着多家公司，包括 SpaceX 和 X（前身为 Twitter）社交媒体平台。</p><p>据《华尔街日报》5 月份报道，特斯拉没有明确的第二把手，但<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-executive-elon-musk-cfo-zach-kirkhorn-b1998ae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">董事会成员曾讨论过</a>柯克霍恩可能接替马斯克担任首席执行官。</p><p>早盘交易中，股价下跌超过 3%。周末，马斯克表示他可能需要进行<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-surgery-mark-zuckerberg-fight-3598da84?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更多颈部手术</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5CFE9E1C-85FE-4D55-A214-0EAAA6F54763&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 7 月下旬，埃隆·马斯克将 Twitter 的名称改为 X，这是该品牌的重大变化。但这并不是这位科技亿万富翁第一次使用 URL x.com。 《华尔街日报》解释了该网站的过去可能预示着其未来。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>科克霍恩的离职是在特斯拉高层经历了一段相对平稳的时期之后发生的，在其 20 年的历史中，这段时期经历了巨大的人员流动，尤其是在新车发布期间。</p><p>这家电动汽车制造商正准备交付三年多来的首款新型乘用车 Cyber​​truck，并正在增强制造能力，力求成为全球销量最高的汽车公司。</p><p>柯克霍恩于 2010 年加入这家汽车制造商，帮助特斯拉转型为利润机器，同时以首席运营官的身份处理许多日常事务，通过降低生产成本和追求效率来推进公司的增长目标。</p><p>在一份证券备案文件中，特斯拉感谢 38 岁的柯克霍恩对公司的“重大贡献”，并表示他将继续与该汽车制造商合作直至今年年底，以支持“无缝过渡”。</p><p>根据塔内贾的 LinkedIn 简历，45 岁的塔内贾自 2016 年 3 月加入 SolarCity 担任会计业务副总裁以来，一直进入马斯克的商业轨道。</p><p>在特斯拉成功收购太阳能公司后，他留在了特斯拉，马斯克还担任董事长，并于 2017 年成为公司助理财务总监，并随着时间的推移承担了更大的责任。此前，他在印度和加利福尼亚州圣何塞的普华永道会计师事务所工作了近 17 年。</p><p>特斯拉、柯克霍恩和塔内贾没有立即回应置评请求。</p><p>柯克霍恩在 LinkedIn 上发帖感谢马斯克的领导力和乐观精神。</p><p> “成为这家公司的一员是一种特殊的经历，我对自 13 年前加入以来我们一起所做的工作感到非常自豪，”Kirkhorn 说。</p><p>与柯克霍恩在 2019 年初出人意料地宣布接替马斯克的长期密友迪帕克·阿胡贾 (Deepak Ahuja) 后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musks-surprise-pick-for-tesla-cfo-is-a-relative-unknown-11548935508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">接任首席财务官</a>时相比，特斯拉是一家截然不同的公司。</p><p>当时，特斯拉正在努力通过 Model 3 轿车从小众汽车制造商转型为主流汽车制造商。</p><p>去年 10 月底，马斯克收购了社交媒体公司 X 后，柯克霍恩在这家汽车制造商中扮演了更加引人注目的角色。他是三月份投资者聚会的司仪，会上特斯拉重点介绍了在马斯克手下工作的高管。</p><p>与科克霍恩共事过的人称赞他能够与马斯克进行有效的联系和沟通，而自特斯拉成立之初以来，其他高管一直在努力掌握这些技能。</p><p>据《华尔街日报》报道，两位高管之间的关系与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="company-name">苹果</a>首席执行官蒂姆·库克和他的前任史蒂夫·乔布斯之间的关系相呼应。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——威尔·福尔 (Will Feuer) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给丽贝卡·埃利奥特（Rebecca Elliott）： <a href="mailto:rebecca.elliott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rebecca.elliott@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 16:17:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad<author><![CDATA[Rebecca Elliott]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>管理</category><category>管理层变动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>高层管理人员</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>瓦伊巴夫·塔内贾</category><category>扎克·柯克霍恩</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>管理</category><category>管理举措</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>高层管理人员</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>机动车</category><category>替代燃料汽车</category><category>汽车</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Drought Forces Spain to Source Drinking Water From the Sea]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>地中海地区变得比大多数地方更快更温暖和干燥，促使基础设施进行代价高昂的改造<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830762/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="绍水库是西班牙加泰罗尼亚地区最大的水库之一，降雨量一直很少。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>绍水库是西班牙加泰罗尼亚地区最大的水库之一，降雨量一直很少。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115156"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115156"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/margherita-stancati" itemprop="url" rel="author">玛格丽塔·斯坦卡蒂</a></span>埃杜·拜尔 (Edu Bayer) 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日上午 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/drought-forces-spain-to-source-drinking-water-from-the-sea-bad104ec"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>巴塞罗那——如今，在巴塞罗那，用自来水装满一杯水，其中五分之一将是经过处理的海水。另外五分之一将是来自厕所、淋浴和其他城市用途的经过处理的废水。</p><p>这种混合物正在成为地中海国家未来的饮用水。该地区<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">变暖和干燥的</a>速度比地球上大多数地方都要快，迫使这里的人民和政府比其他地方更快地采取行动，寻找新的淡水供应。</p><p>西班牙加泰罗尼亚地区的长期干旱正在引发迅速的变化。巴塞罗那的Llobregat海水淡化厂于2009年启用后的许多年里，它都很少使用，只占该市饮用水的不到5%，而该市的饮用水主要由水库和地下水供应。自去年夏天以来，该工厂一直全速运转，每秒生产超过 500 加仑淡水。</p><p>加泰罗尼亚水务局局长塞缪尔·雷耶斯表示：“人口在增加，商业活动在增加，但水资源却有所减少。” “我们需要改变对水的看法。”</p><p>在地中海沿岸国家，反复发生的干旱和从山区流入河流的水量减少正在导致水利基础设施的重新设计。农民们正在打更多更深的井，并且经常改种需水量更少的作物。从西班牙、以色列到阿尔及利亚，各国政府都在大力投资海水淡化厂，并在更远的地方寻找淡水供应。</p><p>在意大利普利亚地区，地方当局希望建造一条 10 亿欧元、长 100 公里的水下管道，不是输送石油或天然气，而是输送饮用水。计划中的项目将把河水从阿尔巴尼亚穿过亚得里亚海输送到意大利靴子后跟处的普利亚。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830755?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">加泰罗尼亚水务局局长塞缪尔·雷耶斯表示，人们需要对水有不同的看法。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>普利亚没有大河，也没有雪山。目前，该地区正在充分利用其所拥有的少量水资源。地方当局正花费约 17 亿欧元（约合 19 亿美元）来修复和更换漏水的水管，该水管导致当地约 48% 的饮用水流失。</p><p> “我们需要新的基础设施，但我们也需要重新考虑我们对现有水资源的处理方式，”负责监督普利亚水资源管理的运营商 Acquedotto Pugliese 的负责人 Francesca Portincasa 说。</p><p>普利亚的基础设施计划包括建造几个新的废水处理厂和意大利第一个大型饮用水淡化厂，这是普利亚计划在本十年末运营的三个工厂之一。</p><p>气候变化对地中海的影响不仅仅限于干旱。 In a region where roughly 150 million people live close to the coast, rising sea levels are threatening homes, businesses and cultural heritage sites.</p><p> From sand barriers of Egypt&#39;s Nile Delta to floodgates that protect Venice, projects to keep the sea from swallowing the land are multiplying. Some scientists are beginning to consider ideas once dismissed as crackpot, such as damming the Strait of Gibraltar to keep sea levels in check. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830756?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Llobregat desalination plant is Spain&#39;s biggest for drinking water. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830758?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Reverse osmosis and high-pressure pumps are used to remove the salt from seawater at Llobregat.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Much of the Mediterranean region has been in the grip of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/july-heat-waves-nearly-impossible-without-climate-change-study-says-a6dad9e1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a fearsome heat wave</a> in recent weeks, raising mortality rates and putting pressure on overstretched healthcare systems, with the elderly especially at risk. Cities such as Barcelona and Nicosia in Cyprus have set up public shelters to protect people from prolonged exposure to high temperatures.</p><p> Declining access to fresh water poses one of the region&#39;s biggest long-term threats.</p><p> Desalinated seawater has long been a prime source of drinking water in hot, dry countries such as Saudi Arabia, Israel and the United Arab Emirates. Now, desalination is booming in countries whose landscapes provided plenty of fresh water for thousands of years.</p><p> There are downsides to desalination. Turning seawater into drinking water is an energy-intensive process, which makes desalination both costly and bad for the environment. The super-salty brine that is left over is harmful to the ocean&#39;s ecosystem.</p><p> Spain is betting heavily on the technology. Building new desalination plants is the centerpiece of the Spanish government&#39;s plan to deal with the growing problem of droughts.</p><p> In Catalonia, authorities plan to double desalination capacity over the next three years. Last year, the region&#39;s two desalination plants produced 16.7 billion gallons of drinking water, six times as much as in 2009. That water has helped the region to cope with this summer&#39;s extreme heat and drought. In the past, Catalonia has had to resort to extreme measures such as importing drinking water on tanker ships.</p><p> The Llobregat desalination plant is one of Europe&#39;s largest. Seawater reaches the plant from a pipeline that stretches some 1.3 miles into the sea. Then, it is pumped into tanks where coagulants are used to remove grease, seaweed and other substances. The water then goes through two filters to remove smaller impurities. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830763?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A prolonged drought is prompting rapid change in Barcelona.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Finally, it reaches the heart of the plant: a maze of green, blue, yellow and pink pipes where the salt is separated from the water through reverse osmosis. The whole process takes about 5½ hours.</p><p> “There are people here 24 hours a day,” explained Laia Hernández, a representative of the Barcelona plant, during a recent tour of the facility. “Now that we are working at full capacity, maintenance work has to be done quickly.”</p><p> The desalinated water flows to a drinking-water treatment center, where it is mixed with other water supplies, such as water from reservoirs and treated wastewater.</p><p> European Union rules say treated wastewater shouldn&#39;t be used in drinking water. To get around that, Barcelona&#39;s treated wastewater is discharged into a river before being extracted again downstream.</p><p> Rainfall has been so sparse that the Sau Reservoir, one of Catalonia&#39;s biggest, was only 6% full earlier this year. A medieval church, submerged when the reservoir was created in the 1960s, resurfaced. Fishermen were deployed to remove and euthanize the fish left stranded.</p><p> The economic effects of drought are felt most strongly in agriculture. This spring was the hottest Spain has ever recorded, and one of the driest. Farmers were hit especially hard. Insurance payouts to Spanish farmers totaled €772 million in the first half of 2023, exceeding the overall payments for last year as a whole, according to Agroseguro, which handles crop insurance payouts. The overwhelming majority of farmers in Spain are covered by crop insurance, which is subsidized by the state and gives payouts to farmers if their harvests are damaged by events such as extreme weather or disease outbreaks. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830760?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A medieval church that was submerged when Spain&#39;s Sau Reservoir was created in the 1960s recently resurfaced. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830761?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Sau Reservoir at 28% of its capacity.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Scientists at Catalonia&#39;s Institute of Agrifood Research and Technology are trying to help farmers adapt, including how to optimize the use of a declining water supply.</p><p> “Our goal is to produce more food with less water. If we can&#39;t manage that, we will have a problem feeding our population in the future,” said Joan Girona, a water expert at the institute. In one research project, the soil humidity of apple orchards in Catalonia is regularly monitored to determine exactly how much water they need. During the recent drought, Girona advised some farmers to pick unripe fruit, reducing the amount of water the trees need to survive.</p><p> In the Catalan countryside, some 70,000 hectares of farmland used to grow cereals and fruit rely on a 200-mile irrigation network known as the Canal D&#39;Urgell.</p><p> In April, for the first time in its 160-year history, the canal stopped supplying irrigation water. “I couldn&#39;t believe it,” said Sergi Balué, 45, a farmer who relies on water from the canal for most of his fruit production. “From that point on, there was a lot of uncertainty and fear.”</p><p> Worried that his pear orchard wouldn&#39;t survive the spring, Balué did what generations of farmers have done before him: He asked a water diviner for help. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830782?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A canal that Sergi Balué relies on for most of his fruit production stopped supplying irrigation water earlier this year.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Armed with a Y-shape rod, the dowser surveyed the land and indicated a spot on the cracked earth beneath which he said he sensed water. After digging for 100 meters but finding no water, Balué gave up.</p><p> Balué is trying to adapt to water scarcity by collecting more rainwater in small reservoirs. He is also rethinking what crops to grow.</p><p> “I used to have only peaches here,” Balué said on a sweltering afternoon as he stood in the middle of an almond grove. Almonds, he explained, are more drought-resistant than flat peaches.</p><p> “The thinking is: Even with less water, here I can have something to harvest,” he said. “But it makes me feel sad because in this land we have always only grown peaches, pears and apples. Almond trees just aren&#39;t the same.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830765?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tourists swim near the Sau Reservoir.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —José Bautista contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Margherita Stancati at <a href="mailto:margherita.stancati@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">margherita.stancati@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/drought-forces-spain-to-source-drinking-water-from-the-sea-bad104ec</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/drought-forces-spain-to-source-drinking-water-from-the-sea-bad104ec<author><![CDATA[Margherita Stancati]]></author><category> Water Utilities</category><category> Utilities</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Disasters/Accidents</category><category> Drought</category><category> Natural Disasters</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Weather</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>disasters</category><category> accidents</category><category> drought</category><category> natural disasters</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>weather</category><category> water utilities</category><category> utilities </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The U.S. Has a Beef With Europe—Over Cheese]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Feta, Gorgonzola and Parmesan must be made in certain countries to be sold under those names in the EU <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828918/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="The U.S. cheese industry in particular has chafed against EU regulations, which protect almost 300 cheeses." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> The US cheese industry in particular has chafed against EU regulations, which protect almost 300 cheeses. photo illustration: Ariel Zambelich/The Wall Street Journal <span>photo illustration: Ariel Zambelich/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105396"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105396"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kristina-peterson" itemprop="url" rel="author">Kristina Peterson</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 7, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-u-s-has-a-beef-with-europeover-cheese-2880b63e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> WASHINGTON—Klondike Cheese sells its crumbly, Wisconsin-made cheese as feta throughout the US</p><p> In Europe, the company would have to label it white-brined cheese, or some variation that doesn&#39;t mention the word feta. The company doesn&#39;t even bother exporting it there.</p><p> Not being able to call the cheese feta “effectively closes off that entire market for me,” said Luke Buholzer, vice president of sales at Klondike, which makes Odyssey-brand feta cheese.</p><p> Klondike is among the US companies bristling as the European Union expands its list of foods, wines and spirits whose names are reserved for use by traditional local producers. There are now more than 3,500 of these protected items, up almost 28% since 2010, according to data from AND International, an independent food industry research firm. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828923?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Klondike Cheese can&#39;t sell its Wisconsin-made cheese as &#39;feta&#39; in European Union countries.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Klondike Cheese</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The US cheese industry in particular has chafed against the EU regulations, which protect almost 300 cheeses. To be called feta, the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/regional-food-names-are-stumbling-block-in-u-s-european-trade-talks-1445298063?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cheese must be made in Greece.</a> Gorgonzola cheese has to be from Italy.</p><p> Along with increasing the number of protected products, the EU is looking to ease the application process for producers to add their foods to the list. US food makers worry that this will rope in other products, including cured meats. They aren&#39;t challenging the EU protections around “Prosciutto di Parma,” but they want to continue to use the words prosciutto, bologna and chorizo. <em>&nbsp;</em></p><p> “You cannot take something that has been in the public domain for decades—centuries in some cases—and all of a sudden, overnight, decide that name doesn&#39;t belong to the public,” said Jaime Castaneda, executive director of the Consortium for Common Food Names, which represents US food and wine producers on the issue.</p><p> The US and EU are longtime allies and trading partners, but have contended with a lengthy list of disputes over the years, including over <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB859927966751094500?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">poultry</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-struggles-to-turn-steel-imports-green-with-tariffs-4116ee97?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">tariffs on steel and aluminum</a> and differing approaches to genetically modified crops. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d1ff1757-47d7-4af6-9ec5-0be3f9feff64.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The US is the world&#39;s top exporter of food, excluding fish, according to the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations, shipping out close to $200 billion in agricultural exports in 2022, according to the Agriculture Department.</p><p> US food producers have also taken steps to protect some products with geographic ties, including trademarks that protect Idaho potatoes and Florida oranges. The governor of Hawaii signed a law in July requiring more disclosure on labels of Kona coffee blends.</p><p> Castaneda said these are legitimate protections in line with EU regulations for products tightly associated with a specific region. The EU goes too far, he said, in extending those to more common terms.</p><p> “&#39;Idaho potatoes&#39; identifies a specific region,” he said. “When you&#39;re looking for a cheese, you&#39;re looking for a method of production.”</p><p> Castaneda&#39;s group is among those pushing Congress to include a provision in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-republicans-take-command-in-house-fight-over-2023-farm-bill-looms-11668830451?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the coming farm bill</a> that would direct the Agriculture Secretary to work with the US Trade Representative to secure US food makers&#39; rights to use common food terms. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=A32C8378-41AD-4844-981A-F335BCFF688D&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-u-s-has-a-beef-with-europeover-cheese-2880b63e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> With food markets on a wild ride lately, cheese has seen more volatility than most. Yet in supermarkets, prices have remained relatively stable. Here&#39;s why sharp changes in wholesale cheese prices are slow to make it to consumers. Illustration: Jacob Reynolds<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“If not curtailed, this could be a really big injury to our export markets,” said Sen. Tammy Baldwin (D., Wis.), who is backing the bill along with Senate GOP Whip</p> John Thune (R., SD) and others.<p></p><p> EU officials said these protected products, known as “geographical indications,” represent intellectual property and command a premium because consumers associate these products with the regions responsible for their high reputation.</p><p> “The protection of geographical indications enables consumers to trust and distinguish quality products, as well as it protects traditional producers against the misuse of the name of their product,” said Miriam Garcia Ferrer, a trade and agriculture spokeswoman for the European Commission.</p><p> EU officials say their system doesn&#39;t prevent US producers from selling their wares abroad—it only limits how they can label certain items in the EU and other countries where these protections are part of trade agreements.</p><p> US producers said the EU&#39;s labeling restrictions can dissuade them from exporting, or add expense if they choose to continue selling abroad with new packaging. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/280ade20-728c-4dfe-a6a5-013acbfee0e5.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The largest cost “is if you are losing sales because consumers no longer see the cheese name they are used to buying,” said Gaetano Auricchio, president of BelGioioso Cheese of Wisconsin.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>How should the US respond to the EU&#39;s expanding list of restricted food names? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> In Japan and Korea, BelGioioso was forced to change the label of its fontina cheese to “Fontal” and its Gorgonzola cheese to “CrumblyGorg.” It is also in the process of changing its label for Asiago cheese in Mexico to Belgiago, he said, because of trade agreements the EU has reached with that country and others.</p><p> US winemakers are also lobbying to relax some of the EU protections around certain traditional descriptive terms often used on labels, including château and vintage, which US winemakers effectively can&#39;t use on bottles being exported to the EU.</p><p> “We obviously have major concerns about that because it limits the ability of US wine producers to market their wines on a level playing field,” said Charles Jefferson, a vice president at the Wine Institute, which advocates for California vintners. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828748?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Belgian customs destroyed more than 2,300 cans of Miller High Life advertised as the &#39;Champagne of Beers&#39; at the request of Comité Champagne.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Comité Champagne/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The wine industry isn&#39;t challenging some names with geographical significance, such as Champagne, which must come from a specific region in France to be labeled as such. US winemakers have gotten some of their own wines recognized as a geographical indication by the EU, including wines from Napa Valley and Oregon&#39;s Willamette Valley.</p><p> Wines make up roughly half of the products protected by the EU. More than 2,300 cans of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/miller-high-life-cans-destroyed-in-europe-over-champagne-of-beers-logo-25e2c05c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Miller High Life were dumped</a> by Belgian customs in April for bearing the logo “the Champagne of Beers,” at the request of Comité Champagne, a trade organization.</p><p> Write to Kristina Peterson at <a href="mailto:kristina.peterson@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">kristina.peterson@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-us-has-a-beef-with-europeover-cheese-2880b63e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-us-has-a-beef-with-europeover-cheese-2880b63e<author><![CDATA[Kristina Peterson]]></author><category> photo-commission</category><category> Food/Beverages</category><category> Dairy Products</category><category> Non-frozen Dairy Products</category><category> Wine</category><category> Alcoholic Beverages/Drinks</category><category> Beverages/Drinks</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category> Food Products</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Jaime Castaneda</category><category> Charles Jefferson</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>food</category><category> beverages</category><category> dairy products</category><category> non-frozen dairy products</category><category> wine</category><category> alcoholic beverages</category><category> drinks</category><category> consumer goods</category><category> food products </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kim Jong Un Touts North Korea’s Weapons]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Leader&#39;s recent arms-factory visits could signal an intent to export weapons, South Korea says, potentially to Russia <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115149"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830746?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Kim Jong Un was shown in state media photos testing new sniper rifles during a recent visit to North Korean weapons factories.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: str/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115149"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dasl Yoon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 7, 2023 8:07 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-spotlights-weapons-amid-u-s-concerns-about-illegal-arms-trade-3375283c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> SEOUL—North Korean leader <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">Kim Jong Un</a> sought to showcase his country&#39;s defense industries and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-nuclear-weapons-missiles-explained-11610712018?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">its nuclear-weapons arsenal</a> , as US and South Korean officials worry Pyongyang may seek to expand its illegal weapons trade.</p><p> Kim toured North Korea&#39;s weapons factories for three days through Saturday, overseeing production of artillery systems and launch vehicles for nuclear-capable ballistic missiles, Pyongyang&#39;s state media reported Sunday. Last month, North Korea offered another prominent display of its arsenal <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-flaunts-north-koreas-newest-weapons-with-russia-and-china-by-his-side-125399f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">during a military parade</a> , including its largest intercontinental ballistic missiles and new spy drones.</p><p> Kim&#39;s visits to weapons factories are rarely publicized. During the latest visits, Kim ordered factories making artillery and missile engines to boost capacity. He inspected multiple-launch rocket systems and engines for drones that are necessary for North Korea&#39;s “war preparation,” state media said. Kim ordered factory workers to “unleash their creative wisdom and enthusiasm.”</p><p> State-media photos showed Kim testing new sniper rifles and walking past launcher trucks designed for ICBMs that have the ability to reach the US mainland. Kim emphasized the need to modernize the sniper rifles and other weapons.</p><p> On Monday, Koo Byoung-sam, a spokesman for South Korea&#39;s unification ministry, said Kim&#39;s visits to the arms factories could signal an intent to export weapons. “If North Korea is hinting at weapons exports, it is professing it will violate United Nations Security Council resolutions, which is deplorable,” Koo said during a briefing.</p><p> US officials have said Russia <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-is-again-turning-to-north-korea-to-replenish-ammunition-supplies-d79a5318?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is looking to buy</a> more ammunition from North Korea to replenish its stockpiles amid the war in Ukraine. Russian Defense Minister Sergei Shoigu visited the North Korean capital last month, reaffirming Moscow&#39;s military partnership with Pyongyang. “We&#39;re seeing Russia desperately looking for support, for weapons wherever it can find them,” US Secretary of State Antony Blinken said during a visit to Australia in late July.</p><p> Senior officials from Russia and China attended the July military parade in Pyongyang marking the 70th anniversary of the armistice that ended fighting in the 1950-1953 Korean War. The three countries have been tightening their bonds in the face of a growing US military presence in the region. North Korea has been a rare supporter of Russia&#39;s invasion of Ukraine, though it has denied that it has been providing arms to Moscow.</p><p> During Kim&#39;s recent visits to the arms factories, he emphasized the modernization of his weapons systems and urged workers to improve the quality of artillery shells. State media didn&#39;t specify the names or locations of the factories. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830747?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The North Korean leader inspected multiple-launch rocket systems and engines for drones that are necessary for the country&#39;s &#39;war preparation,&#39; state media said.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: str/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> While Kim&#39;s mentions of war preparations are in response to the US&#39;s and South Korea&#39;s increasing military cooperation, the rare publicizing of his weapons-factory visits is aimed at Moscow, said Hong Min, a senior fellow at the Korea Institute for National Unification, a state-funded think tank in Seoul. State-media reports emphasized improvement in the quality of North Korea&#39;s weapons systems and showcased conventional weapons as well as missiles that few countries are willing to supply to Russia, Hong added.</p><p> “This is a very intentional sales pitch,” Hong said.</p><p> When Kim hosted Shoigu, the Russian defense minister, in July, they visited a weapons exhibition featuring Pyongyang&#39;s missiles and its newest drones that resemble US aircraft.</p><p> As Washington has increased military cooperation with Seoul and Tokyo to counter Pyongyang&#39;s growing nuclear and missile threat, North Korea has found an opportunity to deepen its alignment with China and Russia for a much-needed economic lifeline and a shield against additional sanctions at the UN Security Council.</p><p> Kim&#39;s weapons-factory visits are possibly aimed at demonstrating Pyongyang&#39;s military strength in light of continuing joint drills involving the US and South Korea, Koo, the unification ministry spokesman, said Monday. Washington and Seoul plan to conduct their next round of military exercises later this month. North Korea has protested Washington&#39;s expanded joint military exercises with Seoul and Tokyo, and the US deployment of more strategic assets to the region.</p><p> Write to Dasl Yoon at <a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1A143373-3034-4A8C-BC6E-4D8C2EB204BF&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fkim-jong-un-spotlights-weapons-amid-u-s-concerns-about-illegal-arms-trade-3375283c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> From a more powerful intercontinental ballistic missile to hypersonic ones, North Korea has been displaying new weapons alongside its nuclear bombs and submarines. WSJ takes a look at the regime&#39;s growing arsenal to see what message it sends to the world. Composite: Diana Chan<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 12:07:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-spotlights-weapons-amid-us-concerns-about-illegal-arms-trade-3375283c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-spotlights-weapons-amid-us-concerns-about-illegal-arms-trade-3375283c<author><![CDATA[Dasl Yoon]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>nkexperiment</category><category> Aerospace/Defense</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Armed Forces</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Military Action</category><category> Weapons Programs</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Kim Jong Un</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>armed forces</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>military action</category><category> weapons programs</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>aerospace</category><category> defense</category><category> industrial goods </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Real-Estate Haven Turns Perilous With $1 Trillion Coming Due]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Apartment buildings rose in value for years, but surging interest rates loom over sector&#39;s property owners now <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830485/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="随着租金稳步上涨，投资者抬高了多户住宅的价格。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Investors bid up prices for multifamily buildings as rents steadily increased. Richard B. Levine/Zuma Press <span>Richard B. Levine/Zuma Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112088"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112088"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/konrad-putzier" itemprop="url" rel="author">Konrad Putzier</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/will-parker" itemprop="url" rel="author">Will Parker</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 7, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Apartment buildings, long considered a real-estate haven, are emerging as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/houston-apartment-owner-loses-3-200-units-to-foreclosure-as-multifamily-feels-the-heat-fb3d0e75?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the next major trouble spot</a> in the beleaguered commercial-property world.</p><p> Investors bid up the prices of multifamily buildings for years, attracted by steadily rising rents and the prospect of outsize returns. Many took on too much debt, expecting they could raise rents fast enough to pay it down.</p><p> Unlike office buildings and malls, which have been hit hard by remote work and e-commerce, rental apartments have low vacancy rates. The apartment sector&#39;s main problem isn&#39;t a lack of demand—rents have soared since 2020—it is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-bet-that-high-rates-will-linger-61cdaeb7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">interest rates</a> .</p><p> The sudden surge in debt costs last year now threatens to wipe out many multifamily owners across the country. Apartment-building values fell 14% for the year ended in June after rising 25% the previous year, according to data company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSGP" class="">CoStar</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> That drop is roughly the same as the fall in office values. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830530?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Many apartment-building investors took on too much debt, expecting that they could raise rents fast enough to pay it down.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: David Paul Morris/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Mortgage delinquencies in the multifamily category are low but increasing. Borrowing costs have doubled, rent growth is slowing and building expenses are rising. Data provider Trepp earlier this year identified one type of rental-apartment debt as accounting for a large share of the commercial mortgages at risk of default.</p><p> Apartment landlords face a “hydrogen-bomb scenario,” said Peter Sotoloff, a veteran real-estate finance executive and founding member of Blackstone&#39;s property debt business.<br><br> Outstanding multifamily mortgages more than doubled over the past decade to about $2 trillion, according to the Mortgage Bankers Association. That is nearly twice the amount of office debt, according to Trepp. The data provider adds that $980.7 billion in multifamily debt is set to come due between 2023 and 2027. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830785?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “Everyone is focused on office,” Sotoloff said. The risk of apartment defaults, he added, “is a really big issue that is not getting the attention it deserves.”</p><p> Multifamily-building owners in Los Angeles, Houston and San Francisco have defaulted on loans against thousands of apartments. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BX" class="">Blackstone</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the world&#39;s largest alternative-asset manager, has defaulted on mortgages on 11 Manhattan apartment buildings, according to a person familiar with the matter. A spokeswoman for Blackstone said the buildings have unique issues and are “not representative of the strength we&#39;re seeing in our broader rental-housing portfolio.”</p><p> Apartment buildings have a reputation as a lower-risk commercial real-estate investment. They have performed relatively well even at times of recession, including during the 2008-2009 financial crisis when the housing market crashed. People always need a place to live, and during times of crisis former homeowners would flood into the rental market.</p><p> Inflation also allowed landlords to raise rents higher than usual, which boosted the values of their buildings. Asking rents rose 25% over 18 months spanning 2021 and 2022, according to rentals website Apartment List. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> With housing in short supply, developers are converting more empty offices into apartments. But not all buildings are candidates for reuse, even as more than 1 billion square feet of office space sits vacant across the US Photo Illustration: Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>To many investors, these factors <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rising-interest-rates-concern-apartment-building-owners-renters-11653393600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">justified paying high prices</a> . Apartment-building owners often borrowed more than 80% of the building value from bond markets. Most apartment loans are fixed-rate, long-term mortgages. During the pandemic, however, investors took out more <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bonds-backed-by-apartments-are-under-stress-as-housing-market-cools-9717d617?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">shorter-term, floating-rate loans</a> .</p><p> Many of these investors raised rents aggressively, betting that they could sell the buildings or refinance their debt at much higher valuations once their buildings generated higher rental income.</p><p> But few anticipated that interest rates could rise so quickly, pushing down building values and forcing landlords to refinance at much higher rates. Regional banks, a crucial source of funding, are lending far less today, making it harder to refinance mortgages. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Rent growth has slowed</a> sharply in many US cities <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">,</a> while inflation and growing insurance premiums have raised the cost of running buildings. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830093?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> A new crop of private real-estate firms, funded mostly by floating-rate debt and small-investor cash, have become bigger competitors in the multifamily market. Some paid higher prices based on rosy expectations of steep rent increases for years to come. Now, they are having trouble making the numbers work.</p><p> Los Angeles-based Tides Equities has acquired more than $6.5 billion in rental property since 2016, mostly lower- and middle-income apartment buildings in Southwestern cities. In 2021, at a property in a Dallas suburb, the company expected to push up rents 44% over the course of three years, ratings-agency reports show.<br><br> In June, Tides told investors the strategy wasn&#39;t going as planned. Renters were “becoming too tight on cash,” the company said in a letter. Some properties were no longer earning enough money to cover debt payments, and investors would likely need to put in more money to save buildings from default, the letter said.</p><p> In an interview, Tides&#39;s co-founders Sean Kia and Ryan Andrade said they were working with lenders on ways to avoid default at properties that faced difficulties.</p><p> Houston-based Nitya Capital, owner of about $3 billion of multifamily buildings, notified investors in March that it was slashing profit expectations because of steeper interest rates.</p><p> “We are essentially paying the higher mortgage costs instead of making cash distributions,” Nitya Chief Executive Swapnil Agarwal wrote in an investor letter.</p><p> Apartment landlords still have reasons for optimism. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FNMA" class="company-name">Fannie Mae</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FMCC" class="company-name">Freddie Mac</a> offer a reliable source of government-backed lending even as banks retreat. Most analysts expect housing shortages, and high rents, to persist. If interest rates come down, property prices could bounce back quickly. Multifamily owners with fixed-rate mortgages are better positioned to ride out any near-term turbulence.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>What is your outlook for commercial real estate? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> Still, other threats are mounting. The unusually high number of new apartment buildings opening this year and next, especially on the higher end of the rental market, poses a supply concern.</p><p> Further, apartment-building values are more vulnerable to higher rates than their commercial counterparts because they are closely tied to the price of 10-year Treasury notes, which plunged as rates rose, said Chad Littell, CoStar&#39;s national director of capital-markets analytics.</p><p> Even some veteran real-estate investors that weathered past storms look vulnerable. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NZ/XNZE/GSH" class="">Veritas Investments</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> one of San Francisco&#39;s largest landlords, and partners defaulted on debt backing 95 rental buildings during the past year. It stands to lose more than one-third of its San Francisco portfolio as a result.</p><p> “The multifamily real-estate sector is facing many of the same financial challenges as have been reported on for other asset classes including office, retail and hotel-hospitality” the company said earlier this year.</p><p> Write to Konrad Putzier at <a href="mailto:konrad.putzier@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">konrad.putzier@wsj.com</a> and Will Parker at <a href="mailto:will.parker@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">will.parker@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528<author><![CDATA[Konrad PutzierWill Parker]]></author><category> housing</category><category> commercial re</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Housing</category><category> Commercial RE</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Blackstone</category><category> BX</category><category> Fannie Mae</category><category> FNMA</category><category> Freddie Mac</category><category> FMCC</category><category> CoStar Group</category><category> CSGP</category><category> Good Spirits Hospitality</category><category> GSH.NZ</category><category> NZ:GSH</category><category> Peter Sotoloff</category><category> Sean Kia</category><category> Ryan Andrade</category><category> Swapnil Agarwal</category><category> Chad Littell</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Hell of Living In a Home With Any Celebrity Connection]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Move over, Graceland. Thanks to social media and Google maps, even mildly famous houses now get tons of visitors—some owners get a kick out of it. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828333/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="A house where Taylor Swift once lived, on Cornelia Street in Manhattan, draws people who want to take photos." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> A house where Taylor Swift once lived, on Cornelia Street in Manhattan, draws people who want to take photos. Jennifer Kerrigan/The Wall Street Journal <span>Jennifer Kerrigan/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093607"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093607"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/candace-taylor" itemprop="url" rel="author">Candace Taylor</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 7, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/celebrity-houses-famous-homes-6ba91102"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> NEW YORK—It&#39;s a Tuesday evening on Cornelia Street, a side street in Manhattan&#39;s West Village. A little after 6 pm, 17-year-old Lily Posner and her grandmother stroll down the street and come to a stop about half way down the block. There, they start snapping photos of a brick house. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          twocolumn
"><figure class="media-object-image img-twocolumn"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="140" height="61" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830826?width=140&amp;height=61" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><p> Posner, clad in a gray hoodie and carrying a shopping bag, explains she is a “very big fan” of Taylor Swift, who rented the house around 2016 and immortalized it in her song “Cornelia Street.” A Vermont resident, Posner spent the day shopping and sightseeing before stopping by to get a glimpse of Swift&#39;s former abode.</p><p> Though the singer never owned the house and only lived there for a brief time, Posner&#39;s enthusiasm is undimmed; she calls the Cornelia Street visit a highlight of their trip. “I love the song,” she says. “It&#39;s iconic.” As she speaks, another pair of fans arrive at the house to take photos. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="944" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828344?width=700&amp;height=944" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Lily Posner at Taylor Swift&#39;s former apartment</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Lily Posner</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> A few blocks away, a similar scene is unfolding in front of 66 Perry Street, a brownstone that appeared as the home of Carrie Bradshaw in the TV series “Sex and the City.” Never mind that the series ended in 2004: Every few minutes, another group meanders down the tree-lined street to snap photos of the house. A chain strung across the stoop bears a “Private Property: No Trespassing” sign as well as instructions to keep voices down and stay off the steps.</p><p> Step aside, Graceland. These days, a home doesn&#39;t have to be especially famous to get a steady stream of curious—and sometimes pushy—visitors. Thanks to social media and Google maps, homes that are even moderately well-known can now be inundated with people eager to take selfies or relive on-screen moments. This can come as a surprise to the homeowners, who find themselves fielding requests for tours or overhearing impromptu singalongs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830980?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The owner of the home where Mark Twain died says the number of visitors stopping by has steadily increased.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Aerial 360 Solutions</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “Now because everything is online, anybody who has a passing interest can find out exactly where it is in about five minutes,” says Erika de Santis, who owns the Redding, Conn., house where Mark Twain died. She says the number of so-called Twainiacs stopping by to see her home has steadily increased in recent years.</p><p> In Albuquerque, NM, owners of the house that served as the home of Walter White in “Breaking Bad” erected a fence around the property after fans kept throwing pizzas on the roof, in homage to a pivotal scene in the show. When Compass real-estate agent Larissa Petrovic recently showed Swift&#39;s former Cornelia Street home to potential buyers, she says they were shocked by the number of people photographing it. They didn&#39;t make an offer. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="394" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816018?width=700&amp;height=394" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A scene from &#39;Breaking Bad&#39; involved pizza on the roof of a home in New Mexico.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: AMC</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Real-estate agent Danny Brown of Compass has the listing for the Los Angeles house that served as the exterior of the home on “The Brady Bunch.” His client, HGTV, renovated the interiors to match the sitcom&#39;s set, and put it on the market in May for $5.5 million. “It&#39;s been bonkers, with nonstop showing requests,” Brown says. Most aren&#39;t from serious buyers, but people simply trying to get a look inside. Recently, potential buyers came dressed in “full &#39;70s retro-wear,” Brown says. While they were touring the home, two women stood outside for 20 minutes singing the show&#39;s theme song. The potential buyers headed outside to join the serenade. “It was a whole chorus of five or six people singing the theme song,” Brown says. “That&#39;s the sort of crazy stuff that happens in front of this house.”</p><p> The house is now in contract and set to close in a few weeks, he says. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/fc5d16f6-3f02-4ee9-add8-6a35b8286fcc.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> In 2017, John and Katie Tashjian bought the South Carolina house where the &#39;80s movie “The Big Chill” was filmed. When they bought the circa-1850s house, it was in disrepair and still had two sets in it from the filming of the movie, says John Tashjian, a real-estate developer. The couple embarked on a three-year renovation before moving in full-time.</p><p> The home is a local landmark. Still, they were taken aback by the number and persistence of visitors. Every weekday some 25 to 50 people stop by and twice that many on weekends, John Tashjian says. In addition to snapping photos, many belt out songs from “The Big Chill,” especially “Joy to the World” by Three Dog Night.</p><p> “I can&#39;t tell you how many times I&#39;ve heard people singing &#39;Jeremiah Was a Bullfrog&#39; like it&#39;s some kind of old-time revival,” he says.</p><p> When they first moved in, they left the property&#39;s gates open. So many people ventured into their yard, however, that they ended up putting in gates that close automatically. “There were people sitting in our yard, taking videos,” says John Tashjian. Others brought picnics or re-created scenes from the movie. Some knocked on the door to ask for a tour. Sometimes he obliged, depending on “what kind of mood I was in.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828350?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Katie and John Tashjian at their home in South Carolina. The house, featured in the movie &#39;The Big Chill,&#39; attracts many visitors.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Charlotte Berkeley </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="470" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829803?width=700&amp;height=470" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Cast members of &#39;The Big Chill,&#39; Glenn Close, Kevin Kline, Meg Tilly, William Hurt, Tom Berenger, Mary Kay Place, Jeff Goldblum, and JoBeth Williams, in 1983.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Everett Collection</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> These days, visitors are welcome to take photos from outside the gates, he says. He does get irritated when looky-loos drive on the grass, or knock over the steel bollards that edge the property. Still, he realizes attention comes with the territory. “If you&#39;re going to own this house, you can&#39;t be surprised by the reception,” he says. “It&#39;s like living next to an airport and complaining about airplanes.”</p><p> One reason for the growing attention to these homes is that streaming services make older TV and movies instantly available.</p><p> In 2012, real-estate agent Adele Curtis represented the buyers of the Winnetka, Ill., house where the 1990 movie “Home Alone” was filmed. “At that point, it was kind of ho-hum, it&#39;s the &#39;Home Alone&#39; house,” she says. While at the brick Georgian, she never noticed passersby taking pictures.</p><p> Nowadays, fans can be spotted outside the house snapping photos “at any time of the day or night,” she says. “It&#39;s become more popular than it ever was.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816038?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Fans take photos outside the house featured in the movie &#39;Home Alone&#39; in Winnetka, Ill.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Youngrae Kim/The Washington Post/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="474" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830846?width=700&amp;height=474" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Macaulay Culkin in 1990&#39;s &#39;Home Alone.&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: 20th Century Fox/Everett Collection</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> James C. Barry, whose parents were longtime owners of the house that served as the home of Blanche, Dorothy, Rose and Sophia on “The Golden Girls,” says the show had a surge in popularity before the family sold it in 2020. Once, a man knocked on the door and said his girlfriend was a huge fan of the show, and asked if he could propose to her in the home&#39;s driveway. Barry&#39;s mother agreed, and after he popped the question, “she came out with some champagne to toast them.” The couple sent Christmas cards every year expressing their appreciation.</p><p> Mallory Crichton and her husband live next door to what is known in Los Angeles as the Black Dahlia murder house, where an unsolved 1947 murder is believed to have taken place. Both homes are gated and set back from the street, so the many true-crime fans who stop by each week often get confused and take pictures of Crichton&#39;s “pretty normal” three-bedroom rental instead.</p><p> She points them in the right direction if she happens to be home, but she&#39;s not always around so many likely return home with photos of her abode instead. “But good for them,” she says. “Ignorance is bliss. They and their friends probably don&#39;t know that it&#39;s not actually the Black Dahlia murder house.”</p><p> Write to Candace Taylor at <a href="mailto:candace.taylor@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">candace.taylor@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7014063b-a894-4b50-b6a3-a3b3e88591aa.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/celebrity-houses-famous-homes-6ba91102</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/celebrity-houses-famous-homes-6ba91102<author><![CDATA[Candace Taylor]]></author><category>阿赫德</category><category>wsjmansion</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Celebrities</category><category> Living/Lifestyle</category><category> Real Estate/Property</category><category> Real Estate Listings</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>celebrities</category><category> living</category><category> lifestyle</category><category> real estate</category><category> property</category><category> real estate listings</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ukraine’s Ammunition Chief Battles to Boost Production]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Former head of state railway company fights to bring Ukraine&#39;s defense industry up to speed as war with Russia drags on <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829765/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Oleksandr Kamyshin says it will take years for Ukraine to meet its current level of ammunition demand." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Oleksandr Kamyshin says it will take years for Ukraine to meet its current level of ammunition demand. Joseph Sywenkyj for The Wall Street Journal <span>Joseph Sywenkyj for The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001110574"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001110574"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/isabel-coles" itemprop="url" rel="author">Isabel Coles</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 7, 2023 12:03 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-ammunition-chief-battles-to-boost-production-563e5fac"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> KYIV, Ukraine—Like any good boss, Oleksandr Kamyshin keeps on top of production numbers for the factories he oversees. But for Kamyshin, Ukraine&#39;s minister of strategic industries, it is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-again-learns-that-war-needs-industry-33c8ca88?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a matter of life and death</a> : The figures that land on his desk every morning show ammunition output at dozens of Ukrainian factories.</p><p> The availability of artillery shells could prove decisive in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the next phase of the war</a> with Russia, and the 39-year-old is in charge of boosting Ukraine&#39;s production. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-push-to-restock-howitzer-shells-rockets-sent-to-ukraine-bogs-down-f604511a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Western stocks</a> have been run down by nearly 18 months of fighting, and the US and its allies are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-ramps-up-howitzer-shell-production-to-supply-ukraine-replenish-stockpiles-1e6dce54?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">struggling to increase production</a> .</p><p> Any dip in output and Kamyshin immediately gets on the phone with the factory manager to find out what went wrong. “All of them are on a direct line with me,” he said in an interview.</p><p> Ukraine&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-arms-industry-survives-russian-onslaught-to-hit-back-c5c168cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sprawling arms industry</a> fell into decline after the country gained independence from the Soviet Union in 1991. Kamyshin says it is still hamstrung by unproductive practices rooted in the Soviet era. “It&#39;s a complete change of culture,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829767?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ukrainian military patches hang alongside emblems of state agencies and NGOs in Oleksandr Kamyshin&#39;s office.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Joseph Sywenkyj for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Kamyshin has delivered before. As head of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-railroads-have-become-vital-cog-in-kyivs-war-effort-11647000001?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Ukraine&#39;s state railway company</a> , he kept goods and people flowing after the country&#39;s airspace was closed in the early days of the invasion. Ukrzaliznytsia&#39;s trains ferried civilians and foreign dignitaries including President Biden, who <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-kyiv-visit-was-months-in-the-making-bb307fb8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">traveled to Kyiv</a> last year on a train dubbed Rail Force One.</p><p> But bringing Ukraine&#39;s defense industry up to speed in the middle of a war is an even bigger challenge.</p><p> Four months into the job, Kamyshin&#39;s efforts have yielded results. In July, Ukraine produced more than twice as much mortar and artillery ammunition as it did during the whole of 2022, he said.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> That, however, is less an indication of how much Ukraine is producing now than how little it was before, Kamyshin acknowledged. The numbers are secret, but it will be years before Ukraine can produce enough ammunition to meet current needs, he said. “I&#39;m climbing Kilimanjaro,” Kamyshin said. “It&#39;s like the end of the first day.”</p><p> For now Kyiv is dependent on Western countries that are also struggling to increase production after running down their own ammunition stockpiles. The US recently provided Kyiv with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-cluster-munitions-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-against-dug-in-russians-d2dd292f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cluster munitions</a> to help alleviate a looming shortage as Ukrainian forces struggle to break through Russian defenses in the south of the country. European states, too, struck a deal last month mobilizing half a billion euros to boost ammunition production for Ukraine—and for themselves. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="511" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829811?width=700&amp;height=511" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> State arms maker Ukroboronprom, based in Kyiv, has had to boost output while facing Russian attacks.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Gleb Garanich/Reuters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The scramble for ammunition reflects how ill-prepared Ukraine and its allies were to sustain an intense and protracted land war.</p><p> On the battlefield, Ukraine has held its own against a much bigger army. But in the vital struggle to support its combatants with arms and ammunition, it is far behind. Russia—the world&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-war-in-ukraine-hurts-its-arms-industry-creates-openings-for-rivals-c25321c6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">second-largest arms exporter</a> —has continued churning out military hardware.</p><p> Ukraine was once a key center of the Soviet defense industry, but many of the arms factories it inherited upon independence in 1991 fell into decline over the ensuing decades. In the year before Russia&#39;s invasion, Ukraine produced no ammunition at all, according to Kamyshin.</p><p> Western allies stepped in as Ukraine burned through its ammunition stockpiles during the first months of the war, while local defense companies struggled to increase production under Russian bombardment.</p><p> The war was a year old by the time Kamyshin was appointed as chief of the defense industry, but to him it felt like the very first days of the invasion. “Being in charge of a large, crucial, critical structure for your country for the war when nothing works,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829805?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ukrainian forces in the eastern Donetsk region have been burning through stocks of shells at a rapid rate.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Michael Brochstein/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830634?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Members of the repair battalion of the 3rd Tank Brigade work on an armored vehicle at a shop in the Kharkiv region earlier this year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: sergey bobok/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Ukraine&#39;s President</p> Volodymyr Zelensky tapped him as minister in March as the country geared up for a counteroffensive to retake territory occupied by Russia.<p></p><p> Kamyshin&#39;s immediate priority was ammunition, which Ukrainian forces are consuming at a rate of about 90,000 shells a month, according to US officials. To spur production, he visited dozens of factories, which have been dispersed across the country and abroad to make them harder for Russia to strike.</p><p> It surprised Kamyshin to find that some factories weren&#39;t working round the clock or over the weekend, he said. “In the second year of the war everyone should be working 24/7.”</p><p> His new team of like-minded deputies includes a new head of state-owned weapons manufacturer Ukroboronprom. “These people know that you can&#39;t say &#39;Let&#39;s talk Monday,&#39; ” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B4EEDAEB-204A-4D35-A945-2EA739618C35&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fukraines-ammunition-chief-battles-to-boost-production-563e5fac&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Storm Shadow missiles equip Ukraine&#39;s counteroffensive with the ability to hit Russian targets far behind the frontlines. The WSJ explores how the weapon works and why it&#39;s forcing Moscow to rethink its logistics. Photo Illustration: Nayon Cho (Published Aug. 1)<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Ukraine isn&#39;t the first country whose industry was unprepared at the start of a war, prompting a sudden pivot involving executives from civilian sectors. In the US at the start of both world wars, successful and often well-paid private-sector business leaders volunteered to help government mobilization efforts, becoming known as dollar-a-year men because regulations forbid official work for no pay.</p><p> Taking a similar approach of borrowing from the private sector in Ukraine, Kamyshin has extended defense companies&#39; contracts to year-end—rather than monthly—and brought in more firms to gear production toward the defense industry. “It&#39;s not rocket science,” he said.</p><p> By the end of the year, Ukraine will be producing NATO-standard 155mm ammunition as well as the Soviet 152mm and 122mm calibers already produced.</p><p> When Winston Churchill became British prime minister in May 1940 as Nazi forces overran France, he appointed newspaper magnate Max Aitken, Lord Beaverbrook, to the newly created position of minister of aircraft production. The frequently intimidating businessman pushed factories to triple fighter-plane production over four months, giving the Royal Air Force enough aircraft to prevail in the Battle of Britain during that summer. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="637" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829770?width=639&amp;height=637" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> During World War II, newspaper publisher Max Aitken was chosen to oversee the UK&#39;s aircraft production.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Kamyshin hopes other companies will follow German munitions maker <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/XE/XETR/RHM" class="">Rheinmetall</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BAESY" class="company-name">BAE Systems</a> and Turkey&#39;s Baykar, which are already moving to open plants in Ukraine. Several US arms manufacturers have expressed interest, Kamyshin said. In return for the risks of setting up shop in a war zone, firms get the opportunity to test and develop weapons on the frontiers of modern warfare, Kamyshin said.</p><p> The US has said it is looking to learn from Ukraine about <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/behind-ukraines-deadly-drones-putins-invasion-and-bidens-limits-5f2f2cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">how to conduct drone warfare</a> . The war has witnessed the greatest use of aerial drones and counterdrone technology in any military conflict. Both sides are employing a full range of offensive and defensive unmanned aerial vehicles and electronic warfare measures aimed at thwarting them.</p><p> Beyond that, Kamyshin said, Ukraine&#39;s defense industry could serve as an engine for economic recovery and underwrite its security when the war is over. “We have an ambition to be the arsenal of the free world,” Kamyshin said, invoking the words of Franklin D. Roosevelt during World War II.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Daniel Michaels contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Isabel Coles at <a href="mailto:isabel.coles@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">isabel.coles@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 04:03:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-ammunition-chief-battles-to-boost-production-563e5fac</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-ammunition-chief-battles-to-boost-production-563e5fac<author><![CDATA[Isabel Coles]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>Firearms</category><category> Aerospace/Defense</category><category> Defense Equipment/Products</category><category> Industrial Goods</category><category> Output/Production</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Products/Services</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Military Action</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> output</category><category> production</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>products</category><category> services</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>military action</category><category> firearms</category><category> aerospace</category><category> defense</category><category> defense equipment</category><category> industrial goods</category></item></channel></rss>